## Dataset

The system was developed and evaluated on three categories of clips:

| Source | Type | Notes |
|--------|------|-------|
| YouTube | Cricket match highlights | Publicly available; search for "cricket edge caught behind slow motion" |
| Broadcast footage | Professional matches | HD clips from TV recordings |
| Custom recordings | Tennis ball + cricket bat | Self-recorded controlled scenarios for ground truth |

**Dataset size:** 20–30 short video clips, each 2–5 seconds long.

> ⚠️ Due to copyright restrictions, broadcast clips are not included in this submission. YouTube clips used for evaluation are publicly accessible. Custom-recorded clips are hosted at:  
> **[Insert Google Drive / OneDrive link here]**  
> *(Ensure sharing permissions are set to "Anyone with the link can view")*

### Recommended clip characteristics

- Duration: 2–5 seconds
- Frame rate: 30–60 FPS
- Resolution: 720p or higher
- Camera angle: Side-on or behind-wicket view with bat clearly visible

---

## Evaluation Metrics

The following metrics are used to evaluate system performance:

| Metric | Formula | Description |
|--------|---------|-------------|
| **Accuracy** | (TP + TN) / Total | Overall correct predictions |
| **Precision** | TP / (TP + FP) | Of all declared contacts, how many were real |
| **Recall** | TP / (TP + FN) | Of all real contacts, how many were detected |
| **F1 Score** | 2 × (P × R) / (P + R) | Harmonic mean of precision and recall |

Ground truth labels (contact / no contact) were manually annotated for all evaluation clips through frame-by-frame visual inspection.

---

## Results

| Scenario | Accuracy |
|----------|----------|
| Controlled / custom recordings | ~85% |
| Broadcast / YouTube clips | Lower (motion blur, camera movement) |

### Success cases
- Clear edge contacts in controlled lighting with a stationary camera perform well
- ROI restriction significantly reduces false triggers from background player movement

### Failure cases
- Heavy motion blur during fast deliveries
- Camera panning or zooming causing widespread frame difference
- Ball too small or partially occluded at moment of contact
- Manual ROI does not adapt if the bat moves far out of the selected region

---

## Known Limitations

- **Manual ROI:** The bounding box must be drawn by the user on the first frame. If the bat moves significantly, the ROI becomes misaligned.
- **No ball tracking:** The system does not independently locate the ball; it only analyzes motion within the bat ROI.
- **Lighting sensitivity:** Large changes in exposure (e.g., floodlights flickering) can trigger false positives.
- **No audio analysis:** The characteristic "snick" sound of an edge is not used (planned for future work).

